injured. In Point of Reckoning, Theodore D. Segal narrates the contested fight for racial justice at Duke from the enrollment of the first Black undergraduates in 1963 to the events that led to the Allen Building takeover and beyond. Segal shows that Duke's first Black students quickly recognized that the university was unwilling to acknowledge their presence or fully address its segregationist past. By exposing the tortuous dynamics that played out as racial progress stalled at Duke, Segal tells both a local and national story about the challenges that historically white colleges and universities throughout the country have faced and continue to face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAfrican American college studentsxHistoryy20th centuryzNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aAfrican American college studentszNorth CarolinazDurhamxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in higher educationxHistoryy20th centuryzNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aRacism in higher educationzNorth CarolinazDurhamxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismxHistoryy20th centuryzNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aRacismzNorth CarolinazDurhamxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478012955zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012955/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles